  "market_context": "Crude oil daily chart trading near a previous month's high around 92.00, with equal highs forming buy-side liquidity. Price had pushed into this premium level and stalled, setting up a bearish continuation scenario from a higher-time-frame supply zone.",
  "key_observation": "Multiple sequential bearish order blocks form as price retraces back up into prior order blocks and small fair value gaps, then displaces and closes below the up-close candles each time — providing repeated continuation entries lower.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Identify the previous month's high near 92.00 and equal highs creating buy-side liquidity as the key premium level.",
    "Step 2: Note a series of up-close candles running into the equal highs, then displacement and a close below those bodies, validating the first bearish order block.",
    "Step 3: Watch price retrace back up into that order block and into a small fair value gap (inefficiency) above it.",
    "Step 4: Observe another series of up-close candles into that important level, followed by displacement and a close below — validating a second order block for continuation.",
    "Step 5: Repeat the logic again as price reaches into the second order block and once more displaces lower, confirming a third stacked order block.",
    "Step 6: Use each validated order block as a fresh point of interest to anticipate continued bearish delivery away from the premium high."
  ],
  "outcome": null,
  "lessons": "An order block is only valid when price first reaches into an important higher-time-frame level (prior month high, FVG, or prior OB). Stacked order blocks in a trending market provide repeated, high-probability continuation entries when each retracement displaces lower.",
